1 third party used for the purpose of satisfying a request or event. The term
2 includes records from mortgage, education, and employment entities.
3 2. A commercial entity that knowingly publishes or distributes sexual material harmful to
4 a minor on the internet from a website that contains a substantial portion of material ,
5 must be held liable if the entity fails to perform reasonable age verification methods to
6 verify the age of an individual attempting to access the material.
7 3. A commercial entity or third party that performs the required age verification may not
8 retain any identifying information of the individual after access has been granted to the
9 material.
10 4. A commercial entity found to have violated subsection 2 or 3 is liable for damages .
11 5. A civil action may be brought against any commercial entity, or third party that
12 performs the required age verification on behalf of the commercial entity, by:
13 a. A parent or guardian whose minor child was allowed access to the material in
14 violation of subsection 2; or
15 b. An individual whose identifying information is retained in violation of subsection 3 .
16 6. An individual authorized to bring a civil action under subsection 5 may seek and the
17 court may award:
18 a. An injunction to enjoin continued violation of this section;
19 b. Compensatory and exemplary damages; and
20 c. Costs and fees, including reasonable attorney fees.
21 7. This section does not apply to any bona fide news or public interest broadcast,
22 website video, report, or event, and may not be construed to affect the rights of any
23 news-gathering organization.
24 8. An internet service provider or its affiliates or subsidiaries, a search engine, an
25 application store, or a cloud service provider may not be held to have violated this
26 section solely for providing access or connection to or from a website or other
27 information or content on the internet or a facility, system, or network not under the
28 provider's control, including transmission, downloading, intermediate storage, access
29 software, or other forms of access or storage to the extent the provider is not
30 responsible for the creation of the content of the communication that constitutes
31 sexual material harmful to a minor.
